HEADWORD: Periapt
<hw>Per"i*apt</hw> <pr>(p⟦ecr⟧r"⟦icr⟧*⟦acr⟧pt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[Gr. <grk>peri`apton</grk>, fr. <grk>peri`aptos</grk> hung about,
<grk>peria`ptein</grk> to hang about; <grk>peri`</grk> about +
<grk>'a`ptein</grk> to tie: cf. F. <ets>p⟦eacute⟧riapte</ets>.]</ety>
<def>A charm worn as a protection against disease or mischief; an
amulet.</def> <rj><au>Coleridge.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now help, ye charming spells and <qex>periapts</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Periastral</ent>⟦br⟧
